<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Sharp' Words Exchanged Between Kantor, Hata </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0502122994 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 5 Feb 94 
Morning Edition p 11 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0502122994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] U.S. Trade Representative [USRT] Mickey Kantor 
returend to the United States on the evening of 4 February after 
holding separate talks with Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata and 
Posts and Telecommunications Minister Takenori Kanzaki in 
succession and exchanging views on new Japan-U.S. economic 
talks. After arriving in Japan on 1 February, he met with Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa, Finance Minister Hirohisa Fujii, and 
other officials and tried to seek a way out of the deadlocked 
economic talks by means of a "political decision." However, no 
progress was made and it seems that the remarks Kantor made 
while he was in Japan made Japanese officials distrustful of him. 
  At the 2 February meeting with Foreign Minister Hata, Kantor 
touched on the issue of objective criteria and repeatedly said 
seven or eight times that "the United States will review its 
ties with Japan if Japan does not accept (the U.S. demands)." 
In response, Foreign Minister Hata said that "we cannot 
negotiate under this kind of threat." Reportedly, sharp words 
were exchanged between them. 
  Because of this, some officials say that "USTR Kantor 
achieved nothing but fueled the confrontation between the two 
countries," (according to a senior official of the Ministry of 
International Trade and Industry). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

