<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Macroeconomic' Policy Key to Framework Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0802131594 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 8 Feb 94 
Morning Edition p 3 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0802131594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] With the 11 February Japan-U.S. summit near at 
hand, a senior Foreign Ministry official commented on the 
outlook for the Japan-U.S. economic framework talks, which will 
become the focal point of the upcoming summit. On 7 February, 
the official stated: "The atmosphere surrounding the ongoing 
economic framework talks will be greatly changed depending on 
whether Japan can indicate its macroeconomic policies during the 
upcoming summit meeting." Thus, he expressed concern over the 
situation in which the government and the ruling parties are 
facing difficulties in working out plans to implement income tax 
cuts. 
  Moreover, in view of the worsening situation in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina and the deadlocked talks between the DPRK 
(North Korea) and the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) 
over the former's suspected nuclear program, the official 
indicated: "At the summit meeting, measures to deal with the 
former Yugoslavia and North Korea issues will be discussed in 
addition to the economic framework talks." 

</TEXT>

