<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S., Russia Propose Pacific Military Exercises </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0402111294 Tokyo TOKYO SHIMBUN in Japanese 3 Feb 94 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0402111294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo TOKYO SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The "Tripolar Forum for North Pacific Security," 
which was held in a Tokyo hotel (under the auspices of the Japan 
Institute for International Issues), ended 2 February. It was 
attended by concerned government and private representatives of 
three countries; Japan, the United States, and Russia. 
  During discussions, which were held for two days, the United 
States and Russia proposed that joint military exercises among 
Japan, the United States, and Russia in north Pacific regions be 
carried out. Japan disapproved the proposal, citing, among 
other things, that: 1) the forum's purpose is not to counteract 
other nations except the three countries; and 2) there are 
things needed to be done first, including fostering trust. 
  At the forum, the participants agreed that it is definitely 
important for Russian reform efforts to take root for stability 
in the region. 

</TEXT>

