<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   JETRO To Aid Sales of Imported Goods </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0502061794 Tokyo KYODO in English 0526 GMT 5 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0502061794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 5 KYODO -- The Japan External Trade 
Organization (JETRO) will start next Tuesday [8 February] 
providing free counters to importers in seven cities to help 
sell foreign products, JETRO officials said Saturday. The 
counters, called "JETRO Import Squares," are aimed at boosting 
the availability of imports outside Tokyo, where the majority of 
importers run shops. 
  Importers can use the JETRO squares for a year free of 
charge, excluding utility costs. The squares will be provided 
in seven major local cities -- Sapporo, Nagoya, Sendai, 
Takamatsu, Fukuoka, Osaka and Hiroshima. 

</TEXT>

