<F P=100> Brunei, Malaysia &amp; Singapore </F>
<F P=101> Malaysia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mahathir: Sabah Should Support National Front </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0802154794 Kuala Lumpur NEW STRAITS TIMES in English 7 Feb 
94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> BK0802154794 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur NEW STRAITS TIMES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Joseph Bingkasan and Rashid Yusof] </F>
  [Excerpts] Kota Kinabalu, Sun. [6 February] -- Kadazans can 
choose from many other capable leaders who are honest, 
hardworking, and who care for the people to lead them, Prime 
Minister Datuk Sri Dr. Mahathir Mohamed said today. 
  He said the people of Sabah, particularly the Kadazan/Dusun 
community, should not sacrifice their well-being by supporting 
Parti Bersatu Sabah [Sabah United Party -- PBS] President Datuk 
Sri Joseph Pairin Kitingan's aspiration to continue as the chief 
minister. [passage omitted] 
  Dr. Mahathir said as Sabah was lagging behind in 
development, 
the people now had the opportunity to be on par with their 
counterparts in other states by giving the mandate to the BN in 
the coming elections. He said a Barisan government would be fair 
to all races. "When the BN makes promises, they will be 
delivered," he said to the applause of the large crowd. Dr. 
Mahathir said Barisan had nothing against the PBS but could not 
get along with its leaders, particularly Pairin, who had proven 
himself to be insincere. 
  He said that during the 1990 general election, Pairin played 
out the BN by pulling out of the coalition a few days before 
polling. "Pairin now wants to return to the BN, but how can we 
trust him?" He urged the voters not to be duped by the PBS' 
tactics of confusing the people that UMNO [United Malays 
National Organization] was trying to grab power in the state. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

