<F P=100> Cambodia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Son Sann Issues Statement Urging Cease-Fire </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0902143494 Hong Kong AFP in English 1208 GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK0902143494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Phnom Penh, Feb 10 (AFP) -- Senior Cambodian 
parliamentarian Son Sann has appealed for a ceasefire between 
the radical Khmer Rouge and government forces, a statement 
released Wednesday said. The ongoing fighting between the Khmer 
Rouge and the government was detrimental to the Cambodian 
people, Son Sann, the leader of the small Buddhist Liberal 
Democratic Party (BLDP), said in the statement. 
  "The Cambodian people...strongly aspire towards peace, a 
widespread and lasting peace which would allow them benefit from 
the proper reconstruction of the country," he added. 
  The BLDP and Prince Norodom Ranariddh's FUNCINPEC [National 
United Front for an Independent, Neutral, Peaceful, and 
Cooperative Cambodia] party were allied with the radical Khmer 
Rouge fighting against the Vietnamese-backed Phnom Penh regime 
throughout the 13-year civil war brought to a formal end with 
the signing of the 1991 Paris peace accords. The peace accords 
paved the way for the UN-supervised elections last May which led 
to the formation of the current coalition government consisting 
of the Phnom Penh party, the royalists and the BLDP. But the 
Khmer Rouge boycotted the polls and continued their guerrilla 
struggle against the government. 
  Son Sann said the victims of the current fighting were first 
of all Cambodian soldiers from both sides. 
  "But it is the people who suffer the most," he said. "The 
inhabitants of combat zones are killed and wounded. The 
survivors have to flee their destroyed homes and abandon all 
their belongings. Many try in vain to seek refuge abroad." 
  Son Sann called on all belligerent forces to declare a 
ceasefire in order "to end or diminish the suffering of the 
Cambodian people." 
  He also called for talks to start as soon as possible to 
implement a peace proposal put forward by King Norodom Sihanouk. 
The king suggested that "acceptable" members of the Khmer Rouge 
be given senior government posts in return for the radical 
faction opening up its zones, ceasing all guerrilla activities 
and merging its fighters with the government's royal armed 
forces. 
  Khmer Rouge nominal leader Khieu Samphan recently said he 
supported the king's proposal but co-premiers Prince Norodom 
Ranariddh and Hun Sen accused him of being "insincere" and 
demanded that the Khmer Rouge obey a ceasefire first and then 
hold the peace talks. 
  Government forces captured the Khmer Rouge's major 
headquarters and logistics base at Anlung Veng, near the Thai 
border in Siem Reap province on February 5, government officials 
said, adding that one of the main objectives of the attack was 
to push the guerrillas towards accepting a ceasefire. 
  Troops were also moving on Khmer Rouge positions to the east 
of Anlung Veng, in remote northern Preah Vihear province, 
co-premier Prince Ranariddh said Monday. 
  Some 2,000 villagers recently fled their homes in the Choam 
Khsan district of Preah Vihear to escape heavy guerrilla rocket 
and artillery attacks on government positions 
  Prince Ranariddh and Hun Sen have also threatened to attack 
the Khmer Rouge's main headquarters at Pailin in Battambang 
province if the guerrillas did not agree to the ceasefire prior 
to negotiations. 
  A western diplomat, however, said the government seemed to 
be 
losing patience with the guerrillas and to be shifting from a 
policy of fighting and talking, to just fighting. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

