<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials Comment on `Wide Gap' in U.S. Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1002131994 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 10 Feb 94 
Morning Edition p 1 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1002131994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report] </F>
  [Text] A government official disclosed on 9 February that a 
U.S. official in charge of the Japanese-U.S. framework trade 
talks has proposed a plan to submit at the 11 February 
Japanese-U.S. summit meeting an "interim report on 
consultations" which includes a side-by-side listing of points 
of dispute between Japan and the United States as they currently 
stand. The United States has apparently taken this step after 
judging that it has become difficult to reach an agreement with 
Japan in such individual trade sectors as automobiles and auto 
parts, over which negotiations have been stalled. Because the 
United States has termed this report as being "interim" in 
nature, there is a strong possibility that the trade talks will 
virtually be extended. Therefore, prospects are that 
negotiations now will turn to dealing with the case of the two 
nations failing to reach an agreement. 
  The interim report plan has been proposed by W. Bowman 
Cutter, deputy assistant to the president for economic policy 
and who is the U.S. official in charge of deputy-level 
negotiations. The report is said to list, side by side, 
Japanese and U.S. assertions over such issues as "numerical 
targets." The agreement reached by Japan and the United States 
last July concerning the new framework trade talks stipulates 
that an assessment be made of the progress in the trade talks at 
a deputy-level meeting prior to the summit meeting and that a 
report subsequently be submitted to the leaders of the two 
nations. 
  A Japanese Government official asserts that "because the 
United States has further pressed for setting numerical targets 
even in the area of government procurement, where negotiations 
have made relative progress, the trade talks as a whole have 
regressed instead." 
  In this connection, a senior official of the Ministry of 
International Trade and Industry [MITI] said on the evening of 9 
February: "No work has been done to narrow the gap between 
Japan and the United States at the resumed negotiations in 
Washington between Koichiro Matsuura, deputy vice minister of 
foreign affairs, and W. Bowman Cutter, deputy assistant to the 
president for economic policy. They are already talking about 
what to do now." 
  On the same evening, MITI Minister Hiroshi Kumagai said, 
"There is a wide gap (between Japanese and U.S. assertions)." 
He expressed the hope that a negative impact on bilateral 
relations can be kept to a minimum even in the case of an 
agreement not being reached. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-28728 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas028__a94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-028-A </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  10 February 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S.'s `Dangerous Gambit' Decision Discussed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1002130694 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 10 Feb 
94 Morning Edition p 3 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1002130694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By correspondent Shigeru Komogo] </F>
  [Text] Washington, 9 Feb -- The Clinton administration has 
taken a tough stand on trade toward Japan by notifying the 
Japanese Government that it will break off working-level 
negotiations under the Japanese-U.S. economic framework talks. 
Because of disappointment over Japan's new package of stimulus 
measures, which fell short of fulfilling the United States' high 
hopes, the Clinton administration appears to have decided to 
break off the working-level negotiations between bureaucrats of 
the two countries and to look for political decisions from Prime 
Minister Hosokawa and Foreign Minister Hata. The Clinton 
administration has decided to do so because of the U.S. 
Administration's long-held view that "if pressure is applied on 
Japan, Japan yields to the United States' trade demands." This 
is unfortunate for Japan. The Clinton administration has 
decided to break off the working-level negotiations in defiance 
of domestic criticism against it for being impatient for trade 
results from the framework talks. Its decision can be termed a 
dangerous gambit. 
  The administration's decision to break off the working-level 
negotiations has been anticipated. In the working-level 
negotiations on government procurement of telecommunications 
equipment and medical instruments held on the morning of 8 
February, before the Clinton administration notified the 
Japanese Government [of the working-level talks' suspension], 
the U.S. Trade Representative made an unprecedented demand that 
"Japan increase its government procurement of foreign-made 
telecommunications equipment and medical instruments by 25 
percent every year" with the aim of having Japan reject this 
demand. The Japanese delegation clearly viewed this demand as a 
"U.S. proposal aimed at bringing an end to the working-level 
negotiations." 
  A member of the U.S. delegation said that "Japan's new 
package of stimulus measures" has prompted the Clinton 
administration to break off the working-level negotiations. The 
Japanese Government originally was supposed to decide to cut the 
income tax for three years, but now it has decided to cut it for 
only one year. In response, the Clinton administration has 
expressed its dissatisfaction. 
  In cabinet-level negotiations, the U.S. side will try to 
wring a commitment from the Japanese side under which Japan will 
go along with the United States on numerical targets and will 
cut its income tax for many more years. The Clinton 
administration thinks that toward this end, it is wise to opt 
for negotiations with Japan's foreign minister, who is 
considered to be "close to the prime minister and able to make 
decisions." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

