<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata Reacts `Strongly' to Bentsen's Tax Remarks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1002024694 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 10 
Feb 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1002024694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 10 Feb 94 Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] In a news conference before his departure for the 
United States on 9 February, Tsutomu Hata, deputy prime minister 
cum foreign minister, commented on reports that U.S. Treasury 
Secretary Lloyd Bentsen criticized Japan's comprehensive 
economic stimulus package as "a small step." Hata reacted 
strongly, saying: "The United States may be thinking it is 
something like a tax rebate. The package worth a total of 15.25 
billion yen is the largest in scale in history. The United 
States does not yet understand what it is about." 
  Asked about the view that the United States might incite a 
further increase of the yen value on the exchange market should 
the Japan-U.S. framework talks end in failure, Hata said: "The 
exchange market is something that reflects the fundamentals 
[preceding word published in English] of that nation. An 
incitement by words only does not have a long-lasting effect." 
He then complained harshly: "An official in an influential 
position should be very careful about what he says." 
  Speaking about his talks with top U.S. leaders preceding the 
Japan-U.S. summit meeting, he reiterated the position of not 
accepting U.S. demands in the economic framework talks regarding 
numerical targets. He said: "Japan is making steady progress 
toward removal of its surplus. If I speak frankly, they will 
probably come to understand it." But he added: "I would like to 
hold a dialogue, based on the principle that numerical targets 
cannot be accepted." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

