<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pamphlet Promoting Market Opening Prepared </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1002054194 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 10 
Feb 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1002054194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 10 February Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] The Ministry of International Trade and Industry 
[MITI] has prepared a pamphlet in which various examples of 
successful business operations by foreign companies in Japan are 
introduced. This pamphlet, written in English and aimed at 
promoting the advance of foreign companies into the Japanese 
market, gives examples of successful operations by 20 foreign 
companies, including Bayerishe Motoren Werke AG. [BMW], 
Coca-Cola Japan Co., Ltd., Mobil Oil Corporation, and American 
Family Corporation. 
  The brochure, which is entitled: "An Invitation to the 
Japanese Market," describes various facts such as changes in 
each individual company's sales as well as the factors for their 
success. For example, regarding BMW's success, the pamphlet 
cites the following factors: 1) Improvement of the 
implementation of a sales strategy befitting the market 
situation; 2) introduction of products conforming to market 
characteristics such as right-hand drive models; and 3) 
establishment of a network of dealers specializing in its cars. 
In this way, MITI explains that strategies befitting the 
Japanese market have resulted in successful operations. 
  Many factors cited in the pamphlet as accounting for 
successful operations seem to be based on the argument 
maintained by Tokyo at the Japan-U.S. economic framework talks. 
The pamphlet appears to have been designed to promote Japanese 
refutation of the United States' criticism that "due to the 
closed nature of the Japanese market, it is impossible for us to 
join in." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-28735 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas028__a94012" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-028-A </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  10 February 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo, U.S., ROK `Agreed' on DPRK Sanctions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1002061994 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 10 Feb 94 
Morning Edition p 1 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1002061994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Regarding the issue of the DPRK's (North Korea) 
suspected nuclear arms development, by 9 February, Japan, the 
United States, and South Korea had agreed on an understanding 
that if there is no change in North Korea's position of refusing 
inspections by the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), 
economic sanctions by the UN Security Council would be 
inevitable. This was revealed by a government source. The 
Japanese Government -- primarily, the Ministry of Foreign 
Affairs, the Ministry of International Trade and Industry, and 
the Ministry of Finance -- will soon begin studying taking such 
specific measures as restricting trade with North Korea and 
stopping remittances to North Korea by Korean residents in 
Japan. In the Japan-U.S. summit meeting on 11 February, Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa also wants to confirm that Japan will 
maintain close contact with the United States on ways to deal 
with North Korea. 
  Since North Korea declared its withdrawal from the Nuclear 
Non-proliferation Treaty (NPT) in March last year, Japan has 
continued to take a cautious attitude of watching the question 
of enforcing economic sanctions against North Korea, hoping the 
matter will be resolved through the U.S.-DPRK talks and 
South-North Korea dialogue. 
  But the DPRK-IAEA talks underway since late last month, 
which 
came on the heels of the U.S.-DPRK talks, again reached an 
impasse. The situation is now such that (according to a UN 
diplomatic source) it looks as if "there is no choice but to 
begin discussions on economic sanctions against North Korea" if 
the IAEA, at its Executive Council meeting on 21 and 22 
February, decides to move the North Korean question onto the UN 
Security Council. Under such circumstances, Japan, the United 
States, and South Korea held a working-level meeting in New York 
on 4 February to discuss measures to deal with the situation. 
  If the UN Security Council decides on economic sanctions, 
the 
Japanese Government will begin revising government rules on 
trade control, foreign exchange control, and control of entry 
into, and departure from, the country as necessary; it wants to 
freeze money remittance channels such as ships traveling between 
Niigata and Wonsan (North Korea), and foreign banks in such 
places as Hong Kong. 
  According to trade statistics for 1992, Japan-DPRK trade 
included: 28.28 billion yen in exports from Japan of products 
like textiles and machinery products, and 22.68 billion yen in 
imports from North Korea of textiles, nonmetallic minerals, and 
others. It has recently been learned that some Japanese 
products including high-tech equipment have been converted to 
military use. Concerns have also been raised over the reports 
that Korean residents in Japan are sending funds to the tune of 
60 to 100 billion yen a year to North Korea. 
  Furthermore, the Japan-U.S. summit meeting on 11 February is 
expected to take up the policy on North Korea, and to confirm 
the position: "If IAEA security measures do not transpire, Japan 
and the United States should cooperate in deciding on what to do 
as the next step." A government source said: "It is clear 
`what the next step' means." Thus he indicated that enforcing 
economic sanctions will be considered step by step. 

</TEXT>

