<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa Expresses Doubt About Economic Growth </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1002054694 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 10 
Feb 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1002054694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 10 Feb 94 Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] On the morning of 9 February, Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa was briefed on the economic outlook for fiscal 
1994, including a projected 2.4 percent growth target for 
Japan's gross domestic product (GDP). The briefing was given at 
the prime minister's official residence by Tsutomu Tanaka, 
administrative vice minister of the Economic Planning Agency 
[EPA], and other top EPA officials. During the briefing, the 
prime minister expressed doubt about achieving the 2.4 percent 
growth target because the figure was much higher than the 
average 0.6 percent forecast by private research organizations. 
  According to Tanaka, Hosokawa said: "Will this target really 
be attained?" The prime minister's concern stems from the fact 
that recent government economic forecasts have been far from the 
actual state of the economy, Tanaka said. 
  It is very unusual for a prime minister to question the 
economic growth target which has been agreed upon by the EPA, 
the Finance Ministry, and the Ministry of International Trade 
and Industry. 
  Tanaka explained to the prime minister: "When the economy is 
flagging, private research organizations tend to calculate a low 
economic growth rate with a pessimistic view. This is why there 
are big gaps between the economic growth rate forecast by the 
government and those calculated by private organizations. A 
series of government pump-priming measures will bring about the 
desired effect this year and the economy will be put on the road 
to recovery." In this way, he stressed that it was possible to 
achieve the 2.4 percent target. According to Tanaka, the prime 
minister eventually accepted his explanation and said: "I 
understand." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

