<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   More on Proceedings at NAM Meeting in Jakarta </TI></H3>
<H4>   Indonesia's Alatas Opens Meeting </H4>
<F P=102> BK0902103094 Jakarta Radio Republik Indonesia Network in 
Indonesian 0700 GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0902103094 </F>
<F P=104>  Jakarta Radio Republik Indonesia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Indonesian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Foreign ministers of the Nonaligned Movement [NAM] 
today started discussions on realizing the NAM's efforts to 
overcome international political and economic problems. The 
consultative meeting of a number of NAM foreign ministers under 
way at the Department of Foreign Affairs in Jakarta will end 
tomorrow. 
  Opening the meeting this morning, Foreign Minister Ali 
Alatas 
said efforts to end Serbian brutalities and to enhance 
cooperation between the NAM and the Group of 77 are among the 
pressing issues that need to be tackled. Indonesia reiterated 
the need for an immediate lifting of the arms embargo on 
Bosnia-Herzegovina and the convening of an international 
conference on Bosnia. The lifting of the arms embargo will 
motivate the Serbs to honor various UN resolutions and end their 
indiscriminate acts against the Bosnians. 
  The NAM members also need to continue paying attention to 
the 
debts of developing nations. He reminded the NAM and the Group 
of 77 to continue coordinating and consolidating their economic 
activities. 
  The consultative meeting attended by 21 NAM members, 
including Indonesia is expected to overcome the problems in 
preparation for a NAM ministerial meeting to be held in Cairo, 
Egypt in early June. 

</TEXT>

