<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   More on Proceedings at NAM Meeting in Jakarta </TI></H3>
<H4>   Suharto on Bosnia, NAM Cooperation </H4>
<F P=102> BK1002100494 Jakarta ANTARA in English 0907 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK1002100494 </F>
<F P=104>  Jakarta ANTARA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Jakarta, Feb 10 (ANTARA) -- President Suharto in his 
capacity as the chairman of the Nonaligned Movement (NAM) said 
that there has been a change in the pattern of approach to 
implement the North-South cooperation. 
  "Today, the partnership spirit has become the new pattern of 
the North-South cooperation," said the head of state when 
receiving 21 representatives of NAM members here on Thursday. 
  Foreign Minister Ali Alatas quoted President Suharto as 
saying that the North-South cooperation should be implemented on 
the basis of mutual interest and inter-dependency spirit. The 
president said that some resolutions and agreements reached by 
NAM members at the Jakarta's 10th NAM summit 17 months ago in 
the sectors of debt management, population, food etc have been 
implemented. 
  Suharto said he had discussed with leaders of the Group of 
Seven (G-7) industrialized countries debt burden issues 
involving 50 NAM members, 18 of which are classified as the 
poorest countries with the slowest GNP. The G-7 groups the US, 
Japan, Britain, Canada, Germany, France and Italy. The leaders 
of the G-7 have admitted the important roles played by the 
108-member movement in settling the debt burden, Alatas quoted 
President Suharto as saying. 
  Stating that the NAM will always strive to put more emphasis 
on such an economic issue, the head of state said that Indonesia 
is ready to share its experiences with other members in managing 
the debt. 
  "We made an effort to soften the debt burden faced by 
countries having the lowest revenue. It could be the 
re-scheduling of the debt payment," he added. 
  On the Bosnian issue, the head of state has expressed his 
strong support for the establishment of an international 
conference on Bosnia. 
  For this aims, the chairman of the NAM will give inputs to 
the NAM coordinating bureau in the U.N. to follow up their 
planned international conference. 
  Minister Alatas said that he could understand if there are 
some groups of people who have expressed dissatisfaction towards 
Indonesia's inability to send its troops to Bosnia. He said 
that the sending of the troops would never settle the problem. 
  "It would only be worsening the condition," he said, adding 
that the key to the settlement of the Bosnia-Herzegovina issue 
is to implement the U.N resolutions and abide by the 
international law. 
  Alatas strongly asked the Serbian and Croatian forces to 
stop 
the aggression against Bosnia-Herzegovina, saying "If necessary, 
the U.N may use the arms force to stop it." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>
